  <h2>Why It Matters Before Closing</h2>
  <p>
    Septic components are buried, and the more involved repairs sit at the expensive end of home
    ownership. Understanding the system’s condition before closing means any findings can inform
    the negotiation — repairs, timing or price — rather than becoming a surprise afterward. It also
    establishes a baseline for the maintenance the system will need going forward.
  </p>

  <h2>What an Inspection May Include</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Locating the system.</strong> Finding the tank and, where relevant, the drain field — records are often incomplete on older properties.</li>
    <li><strong>Opening and evaluating.</strong> Accessing lids and assessing the condition of components rather than just glancing at the surface.</li>
    <li><strong>Fuller testing.</strong> Some inspections include pumping and flow testing to see how the system handles use.</li>
    <li><strong>Documentation.</strong> A written record of what was found, which is what makes the inspection useful in a transaction.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Scope — and therefore what an inspection depends on — varies, so ask what a given inspection
    includes before comparing options. The
    <a href="/resources/septic-costs/">costs and pricing hub</a> explains why scope drives that.
  </p>

